3 SENATE BILL NO. 1198 By: Mann of the Senate
4 and
5 Kerbs of the House
6
7
8 An Act relating to county resale auctions; amending
68 O.S. 2021, Section 3129, as last amended by
9 Section 4, Chapter 179, O.S.L. 2025 (68 O.S. Supp.
2025, Section 3129), which relates to property bid
10 off in name of county; requiring the Oklahoma Health
Care Authority to release certain liens on certain
11 request of county treasurer; providing for the
Oklahoma Health Care Authority to release certain
12 liens upon request of municipality for certain
purposes; updating statutory language; and providing
13 an effective date.
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 68 O.S. 2021, Section 3129, as
17 last amended by Section 4, Chapter 179, O.S.L. 2025 (68 O.S. Supp.
18 2025, Section 3129), is amended to read as follows:
19 Section 3129. A. On the day real estate is advertised for
20 resale, the county treasurer shall offer same for sale at the office
21 of the county treasurer between the hours of eight a.m. and five
22 p.m., the exact hours of each sale to be determined by the local
23 county treasurer, and continue the sale thereafter from day to day
24 between such hours until all of the real estate is sold and is
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1198 SFLR Page 1
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 conc luded by the county treasurer. The real estate shall be sold at
2 public auction to the highest bidder for cash or certified funds.
3 Online auctions may accept online payments.
4 B. The county treasurer may choose to hold the June resale
5 through an online auction instead of the in-person process as
6 prescribed in subsection A of this section. Such online auctions
7 shall occur during regular business hours and shall follow all other
8 requirements of the resale auction until all of the real estate is
9 sold and is concluded by the county treasurer. The county treasurer
10 may select a firm to conduct the online auction with the cost of the
11 online auctioneer to be added to the sale of each property.
12 C. 1. As used in this section, “nuisance property” shall be
13 defined as property that is deemed unmarketable or unusable due to
14 the existence of liens in excess of the property’s fair market value
15 as shown by the county assessor’s office or due to environmental
16 problems or conditions that exist on the property that would cost
17 more to remedy than the fair market value of the property as shown
18 by the county assessor’s office, or property in which abatement
19 liens have been placed upon the property by a municipality in excess
20 of twenty-five percent (25%) of the property’s fair market value as
21 shown by the county assessor’s office.
22 2. All property must be sold for a sum not less than two-thirds
23 (2/3) of the assessed value of such real estate as fixed for the
24 current fiscal year, or for the total amount of taxes, penalties,
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1198 SFLR Page 2
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 inte rest, and costs due on such property, whichever is the lesser.
2 Notwithstanding, there shall be a reserve minimum bid placed in an
3 amount covering all taxes, abatement costs, penalties, interest, and
4 costs due to a municipality if the right to exercise the reserve
5 minimum bid is noticed to the county treasurer. With the exception
6 of nuisance property, if there is no bid equal to or greater than
7 the sum so required, the county treasurer shall bid off the same in
8 the name of the county. However, the property must be bid off in
9 the name of the municipality if demand is made in writing by a
10 municipality which has outstanding liens upon the property. In
11 cases of nuisance property, the county treasurer shall have
12 discretion to not bid off the property in the name of the county and
13 instead allow the property to remain under its current ownership,
14 unless demand is made in writing by a municipality which has
15 outstanding liens upon the property. “Nuisance property” shall be
16 defined as property that is deemed unmarketable or unusable due to
17 the existence of liens in excess of the property’s fair market value
18 as shown by the county assessor’s office or due to environmental
19 problems or conditions that exist on the property that would cost
20 more to remedy than the fair market value of the property as shown
21 by the county assessor’s office, or property in which abatement
22 liens have been placed upon the property by a municipality in excess
23 of twenty-five percent (25%) of the property’s fair market value as
24 shown by the county assessor’s office. Greenbelts, common areas,
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1198 SFLR Page 3
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 ease ments, retention ponds, and detention ponds may also be
2 considered nuisance property if transference of ownership to either
3 the county or a third party would cause a hardship to the
4 neighborhood or subdivision these areas were meant to serve or to
5 the county or third party.
6 3. The county treasurer shall make the determination, in
7 conjunction with review and approval of the board of county
8 commissioners, upon consideration of the above factors provisions of
9 paragraphs 1 and 2 of this subsection, as to whether or not property
10 constitutes nuisance property. The said nuisance property
11 determination may be made at any time during the year, including
12 before or immediately after the June resale. In the case of a
13 nuisance property that has liens from a city or town, if a minimum
14 bid is not made, the city or town shall be credited a bid on the
15 property equal to the amount of the lien of the city or town if its
16 intention to do so is made known to the county treasurer prior to
17 the sale or at the sale.
18 4. In the case of a nuisance property with liens from a city or
19 town, if a minimum bid is not made, the nuisance property shall be
20 bid off in the name of the city or town if its intention to do so is
21 made known to the county treasurer prior to the sale or at the sale.
22 All property bid off in the name of the county shall be for the
23 amount of all taxes, penalties, interest, and costs due thereon, and
24 the county treasurer shall issue a deed therefor to the board of
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1198 SFLR Page 4
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 coun ty commissioners for the use and benefit of the county. All
2 nuisance property bid off in the name of the city or town shall be
3 for the amount of any municipal liens due thereon, and the county
4 treasurer shall issue a deed therefor to the city or town for the
5 use and benefit of the city or town.
6 D. The county treasurers shall provide to the Oklahoma Health
7 Care Authority (OHCA) a list of properties that will be sold at tax
8 resales in their respective counties. Using the information
9 provided, the OHCA shall produce a list for each county of
10 properties on which the OHCA has liens. The county treasurers shall
11 make the list of properties with the OHCA liens available to
12 potential buyers at the tax resales. The OHCA shall file a release
13 of the liens on properties that fit the definition of blighted
14 properties, as defined in Section 38-101 of Title 11 of the Oklahoma
15 Statutes, in the county records of the county where the property is
16 located on which OHCA has liens upon request of that county’s
17 treasurer. The OHCA shall additionally file a release of the liens
18 on properties on which OHCA has liens upon request of a municipality
19 if the property is owned by such municipality and is to be
20 transferred to a not-for-profit entity for a qualified project, as
21 defined in Section 2357.403 of this title, or for another public
22 purpose deemed suitable by the municipality. The filing of the lien
23 release shall not extinguish the debt owed to the OHCA, which may be
24 enforced through any legal means available to the OHCA.
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - SB1198 SFLR Page 5
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 E. The county shall not be liable to the state or any taxing
2 district thereof for any part of the amount for which any property
3 may be sold to such county. All property bid off in the name of the
4 county shall be exempt from ad valorem taxation as long as title is
5 held for the county.
6 F. 1. The county shall not be civilly liable for any
7 environmental problems or conditions on any property which that
8 existed on the property prior to the county’s involuntary ownership
9 of the property pursuant to this section, or which that may result
10 from such environmental problems or conditions on the property.
11 During the period of the county’s involuntary ownership of the
12 property, the person or persons who would be legally liable for the
13 environmental problems or conditions on the property but for the
14 county’s ownership shall continue to be liable for such
15 environmental problems or conditions.
16 2. In addition, the county shall not be subject to civil
17 liability with regard to any actions taken by the county to
18 remediate any problems or conditions on the property resulting from
19 the environmental problems or conditions if the remedial action is
20 not performed in a reckless or negligent manner.
21 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
22 COMMITTEE REPORT BY: COMMITTEE ON LOCAL AND COUNTY GOVERNMENT
